<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-452-202  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 452 202.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 24 1989 v6 n29 p14(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Canon to launch 2M-byte optical card. (Canon U.S.A. Inc.) (productannouncement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Canon U.S.A. Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Canon Optical Memory Card (Data capture device) (productintroduction)Canon RW-10 Reader/Writer (Disk drive) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSmart cardsDisk DrivesOptical Memory.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   What's in the cards for optical storage technology? (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Upping the ante in the nascent market for credit-card-sized data cards, CanonU.S.A.andP;  Inc. recently unveiled new optical technology that improves uponmagnetic and integrated-circuit designs by allowing users to store graphicsdata as well as alphanumeric information.andM;Canon's Optical Card System technology embeds optical-recording material onto2M-byte plastic cards, allowing pictures, X-rays, fingerprints and othergraphical images to be stored along with alphanumeric data.andM;Users can read and write to the credit-card-sized write once/read many (WORM)cards via Canon's RW-10 Reader/Writer drive.andM;Unlike integrated-circuit (IC) cards and magnetic cards, the Optical MemoryCard is not susceptible to static electricity or magnetic forces, and it ismore difficult to alter, according to Bruno Dosso, regional sales manager ofthe medical products department in the Canon Optics Division, in Jericho,N.Y.andM;In addition, the Optical Memory Card's storage capacity is higher and itsprice is lower, according to Dosso.andM;The Canon Optical Card System is currently being field-tested in Japanesehealth-care facilities, according to Dosso.andP;  In this application, eachpatient carries a plastic Optical Memory Card, which includes medicalrecords, X-ray images, cardiograms and other relevant data.andM;The data and pictures are read by the Canon RW-10 Reader/Writer drive andviewed on a PC-compatible computer screen.andM;Other intended applications for the Optical Memory Card include personal IDcards, automobile record cards and high-security access cards, Canonofficials said.andM;Canon plans to ship sample models of the Optical Card System by January 1990,with full production slated for January 1991, said Dosso.andM;Pricing on the the RW-10 Reader/Writer drive will be about $1,500 to $2,000,while Optical Memory Cards will be $5 each, according to Dosso.andM;Canon Optics Division can be contacted at (516) 933-6300.andO;</TEXT></DOC>